On HIV, non-communicable diseases in eight key points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as cardiovascular diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that the use of tobacco, sedentary lifestyle, poor nutrition, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the likelihood of dying prematurely from non-transmissible diseases.
However, despite widespread knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to increase.
It was in this context that the networks of alliances for non-communicable diseases came together from December 9 to 11 for the second Global Forum of the Alliance for Non-Communicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating nanotechnologies, they should draw inspiration from the HIV/AIDS activism movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress achieved.
While the battle is not yet won, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against MNTs can help reverse this epidemic.
However, in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the MNT community as being "awaiting an electroshock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from the activists in the fight against AIDS.
While the world's attention focuses on preventing NTDs (Neglected Tropical Diseases), those striving to combat avoidable diseases should draw inspiration from the ABCs of AIDS-fighting organizations.
The first letter that the MNT community should take into account is "A", as in activism.
Sure, here is the translation of the given French sentence into English:  "Any person over 40 years old surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in 'die-in' actions during scientific conferences all around the world."
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have put pressure on governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the MNT Community must adopt a more daring approach to budgets - the "B" of the movement's AIDS fight strategy.
The civic organization and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but the organization and maintenance of a broad coalition require money.
The movement fighting against AIDS was clear about this from the beginning and put pressure to obtain resources to effectively support its awareness-raising and accountability activities.
"C" represents coalitions: the AIDS-fighting movements did not take long to realize that progress comes only with multiple supports.
The activists have established connections between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns function better when they bring together internal and external leaders with government powers, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The movement fighting against AIDS has also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for the spread of its support.   To make it more natural in English, we can modify it slightly to:  "The movement fighting AIDS has also recognized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for the expansion of its support."
Thus, "D", the key determinant of success, consisted of drawing attention to the interconnectivity of the challenge.
For example, lobbying educational leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
The MNTs are not less isolated in their causality and also undergo a multisectoral approach to prevention.
The engagement - "E" - has been what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By drawing strategic inspirations from the disability rights movement, which had championed the catchphrase "Nothing About Us Without Us," AIDS advocates demanded the involvement of existing organizations in addressing the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its governing board for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply integrated into the movement against AIDS that it would almost be unimaginable for an AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
The disease prevention movements must also develop convincing stories, and "F" - the formulation of the question - is essential for the HIV community to gain political leadership support.   Note: The letter "F" in the original sentence seems to be a placeholder or abbreviation without a specific meaning provided. If "F" is meant to stand for something specific in this context, please provide the full term for a more accurate translation.
In particular, access to AIDS treatments has been presented as an issue of economic justice.
Formulating the story this way leads to a significant reduction in medication prices, to the point where more than half of the people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the question for AIDS, and a very pertinent one for the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The HIV community has worked hard to place more emphasis on the lifestyle choices of individuals rather than attributing responsibility to the state for providing healthcare and eliminating legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially regarded as a "gay disease," and gender identity became rooted from the very beginning in the DNA of the AIDS activism movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine the way alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Therefore, the gender must become a focal point for the prevention efforts of mental disorders.
Finally, "H" - human rights - is the foundation of the AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical centers.
The strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The movement against AIDS refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising aimed at children.
We could continue down the alphabet with a list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but we believe it is appropriate to conclude on "H," given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization expose people to greater risks of HIV.
The same applies to MNT.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to wonder: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS advocacy movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to avoidable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The MNT and HIV communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
